attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of a compound name starting with <i>witu</i> ‘wood’ or <i>wīt</i> ‘wide’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England. In Old French initial <i>w-</i> regularly became <i>gu-</i>. The usual Norman forms of the name were <i>Gy</i> or <i>Guido</i>. In medieval Latin the same name is found as <i>Wido</i>. It was a popular name among the Normans, enhanced no doubt by the romance of Guy of Warwick, recounting the exploits of a folk hero of the Crusades."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guy de Coublanc De Bourbonne was born in 1170, in Bourbonne-les-Bains, Haute-Marne, Grand Est, France, his father, Fréderique De Bourbone, was 28 and his mother, Guyette Coublanc, was 27. He married Constance Alix de Traînel about 1190, in Traînel, Aube, Grand Est, France. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in Coublanc, Haute-Marne, Grand Est, France."},"et":{"1170–":"1170–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1174–Male":"1174–Surnud","1176–1179":"1176–1179","–1216":"–1216","1175–1227":"1175–1227","1190–1239":"1190–1239","1142–Male":"1142–Surnud","1143–Female":"1143–Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1143":"1143","1176":"1176","1164":"1164","1142":"1142","1175":"1175","1174":"1174","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","1239":"1239","1227":"1227","1216":"1216","1179":"1179","Abt 1190":"umbes 1190","Coublanc, Haute-Marne, Grand Est, France":"Coublanc, Haute-Marne, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa","Bourbonne-les-Bains, Haute-Marne, Grand Est, France":"Bourbonne-les-Bains, Haute-Marne, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa","Traînel, Aube, Grand Est, France":"Traînel, Aube, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa","Coublanc, Haute-Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, France":"Coublanc, Haute-Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1170–":"1170–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1174–Male":"1174–Kuollut","1